[Event "The Opera Game"]
[Site "Paris"]
[Date "1858"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Duke of Brunswick and Count Isouard"]
[Result "1-0"]

{Played during an opera performance in Paris. Morphy demonstrated perfect development and attacking technique.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 {The Philidor Defense — solid but passive.} (2... Nc6 {The more active choice.} 3. Bc4) 3. d4 Bg4?! {Pinning the knight, but this develops the bishop too early.} (3... exd4 {Better — exchanging in the center.} 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7) 4. dxe5 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 dxe5 6. Bc4 {White already has a huge development advantage.} Nf6 7. Qb3! {Attacking b7 and f7 simultaneously.} Qe7 (7... Qd7? 8. Qxb7 Qc6 9. Bb5 {Winning.}) 8. Nc3 c6 9. Bg5 {Every white piece is active. Black is completely cramped.} b5 10. Nxb5! {The sacrifices begin.} cxb5 11. Bxb5+ Nbd7 12. O-O-O Rd8 13. Rxd7! Rxd7 14. Rd1 Qe6 15. Bxd7+ Nxd7 16. Qb8+!! {The stunning final blow.} Nxb8 17. Rd8# {Checkmate! A perfect game of development and attack.} 1-0
